[[File:Westside Market in Manhattan, NYC IMG 5615.JPG|thumb|upright=1.3|right|alt=several shelves of produce displayed outside of a grocery store on the Upper West Side|A selection of produce outside a grocery store on the [[Upper West Side]]]] In [[New York City]], there is an extensive [[New York City water supply system|water supply system]] that supports several programs and infrastructure pertaining to the city's food supply. City officials, agencies, and organizations cooperate with rural farmers to grow food more locally, as well as protect waterways in the [[New York metropolitan area]]. The [[New York City Department of Education]] operates a school-time and summertime breakfast/lunch program. However, New York City is also [[Supermarket shortage|deprived of supermarkets]] in several neighborhoods, and the city has combatted this issue by allowing extra [[street vendors]] to operate in the city. To encourage food safety, New York City also has a restaurant-grading system that it introduced in 2010. Because of its various food programs, New York City has become a model for food systems internationally.
==Watershed protection and local food== [[File:Central Catskills from Twin south summit.jpg|thumb|right|upright=1.1|alt=the Catskill Mountains watershed, where most of the city's water is derived from|Most of the city's water comes from the [[Catskill Mountains]] [[Drainage basin|watershed]]]] {{for|details on the water system|New York City water supply system}}
Government officials, labor organizers, non-profits, community advocacy groups, and residents have a great dependency on rural farmers who develop New York City's [[local food]] shed. The process of linking agriculture with New York City’s urban markets has been largely built upon the fact that New York City's water supply comes from the protected [[Catskill Mountains]] [[Drainage basin|watershed]] in [[Upstate New York]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.nyc.gov/html/dep/html/maplevels.html |title=Current Reservoir Levels |publisher=New York City Department of Environmental Protection |accessdate=2007-06-04}}</ref> New York City's water supply system, the largest surface storage and supply complex in the world, yields {{convert|1.2|e9USgal|m3}} of water daily, with most of this water originating upstate. This water is unfiltered, and a filtration system would require $8–10 billion in construction as well as $1 million in daily maintenance.<ref name="NYS Dept. of Environmental Conservation 2014">{{cite web|url=http://www.dec.ny.gov/lands/25599.html|title=New York City Water Supply|date=2014-11-07|website=NYS Dept. of Environmental Conservation|accessdate=2017-03-20}}</ref> Instead, New York City's watershed is protected by severe New York City Department of Environmental Protection restrictions that prevent pathogens and nutrients from entering the water supply. As a result of protection of the watershed, New York is one of four major cities in the United States with drinking water that is pure enough to not require purification by [[water treatment]] plants.<ref> * {{cite conference |last=Miele |first=Joel A., Sr |title=Maintaining Water Quality that Satisfies Customers: New York City Watershed Agricultural Program |booktitle=International Water Supply Symposium Tokyo 1998 |publisher=New York City Department of Environmental Protection |date=November 20, 1998 |url=http://www.nyc.gov/html/dep/html/news/tokyo2.html |accessdate=2006-11-17 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20061012182905/http://www.nyc.gov/html/dep/html/news/tokyo2.html |archivedate=October 12, 2006 |df= }} * {{cite web |title=New York City 2005 Drinking Water Supply and Quality Report |publisher=New York City Department of Environmental Protection |year=2005 |url=http://www.nyc.gov/html/dep/pdf/wsstat05.pdf |format=PDF |accessdate=2006-07-17 }}</ref> However, the implementation of such stringent regulations is costly to New York State farmers.<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books/about/Watershed_Management_for_Potable_Water_S.html?id=8sqf1kmdKHYC|title=Watershed Management for Potable Water Supply: Assessing the New York City Strategy|authors=[[National Research Council (United States)|National Research Council]], Division on Earth and Life Studies, Commission on Geosciences, Environment and Resources, Committee to Review the New York City Watershed Management Strategy|date=2000-02-17|publisher=National Academies Press|isbn=9780309172684|language=en}}</ref>
=== Greenmarket === [[File:Union Square Farmers Market.jpg|thumb|left|upright=1.1|alt=a farmer's market in Union Square|The [[Union Square Greenmarket]]]] To protect the water supply from runoff and promote regional agriculture, rural and urban New Yorkers developed an alliance called the ''New York City Watershed Whole Farm Program'', which promotes sustainable agriculture in New York State. With financial assistance from the city, upstate farmers reduce [[pathogen]], [[nutrient]], [[sediment]], and [[pesticide]] runoff.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.iatp.org/files/New_York_City_Watershed_Whole_Farm_Program.htm|title=The New York City Watershed Whole Farm Program|website=www.iatp.org|access-date=2017-03-20}}</ref> Meanwhile, New York City’s urban population serves as a local market for upstate farmers, particularly through Greenmarket, a [[Farmers' market|farmer's market]] founded in 1976 by the Council on the Environment of New York City. Upstate farmers sell their products at Greenmarket locations.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://cityroom.blogs.nytimes.com/2008/08/11/ask-about-new-yorks-greenmarkets/|title=Ask About New York's Greenmarkets|last=|first=|date=2008-08-11 | publisher =The New York Times|work=City Room|access-date=2017-03-20|language=en}} * {{cite news | publisher =The New York Times | title=Answers About New York's Greenmarkets: Part 1 | work=City Room | date=August 13, 2008 | url= //cityroom.blogs.nytimes.com/2008/08/13/answers-about-new-yorks-greenmarkets/ | accessdate=2017-03-20}} * {{cite news | publisher =The New York Times | title=Answers About New York's Greenmarkets: Part 2 | work=City Room | date=August 14, 2008 | url= //cityroom.blogs.nytimes.com/2008/08/14/answers-about-new-yorks-greenmarkets-part-2/ | accessdate=2017-03-20}} * {{cite news | publisher =The New York Times | title=Answers About New York's Greenmarkets: Part 3 | work=City Room | date=August 15, 2008 | url= //cityroom.blogs.nytimes.com/2008/08/15/answers-about-new-yorks-greenmarkets-part-3/ | accessdate=2017-03-20}}</ref>
Greenmarket provides regional small family farmers with opportunities to sell their fruits, vegetables and other farm products at open-air markets in the city. The program expanded to 45 markets in 2006—the largest expansion in its then-30-year history—but the resulting Greenmarket expansions were too small or too infrequently patronized to be profitable.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2006/07/19/dining/19gree.html|title=Greenmarket at 30, Searching for Itself|last=Severson|first=Kim|date=2006-07-19|work=The New York Times|access-date=2017-03-20|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> The most famous Greenmarket location is the [[Union Square Greenmarket]], held four days a week throughout the year. In 2003, 250,000 customers a week purchased 1,000 varieties of fruits and vegetables at the market.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://nymag.com/nymetro/news/anniversary/n_8592/|title=Manhattan Gets Fresh|last=Fishman|first=Steve|date=April 12, 2003|website=[[New York (magazine)|New York Magazine]]|access-date=2017-03-20}}</ref>
{{clear left}}
===School lunches=== New York City provides over 40,000 meals a day to children through the SchoolFoods program. Most of the fruit served in [[New York City Department of Education]]-operated public and charter schools is local. A project to bring New York State apples to New York City school cafeterias has also increased fruit consumption among school children. {{As of|2007}}, policy work was focused on the task of bringing more local food to school lunches to give children healthy meals while supporting agriculture in the region.<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.nytimes.com/2007/10/17/dining/17carr.html | work=The New York Times | title=Local Carrots With a Side of Red Tape | first=Kim | last=Severson | date=2007-10-17 | accessdate=2010-05-02}}</ref> However, there is no plan to expand the program {{as of|2015|lc=y}}.<ref>{{cite web | last=Saul | first=Michael Howard | title=New York’s Free School-Lunch Program Hits Limits | website=WSJ | date=2015-02-18 | url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/new-yorks-free-school-lunch-program-hits-limits-1424310977 | accessdate=2017-03-21}}</ref>
The NYCDOE also has a summer-meals program operated by SchoolFoods, which offers free lunches to children under 18.<ref name=":0">{{Cite news|url=http://abc7ny.com/archive/9151844/|title=New York City to offer free summer meals for children 18 years and younger|last=|first=|date=June 25, 2013|work=ABC7 New York|access-date=2017-03-21|language=en}}</ref> These summer lunches are distributed at over 1,100 parks, pools, libraries, schools, and shelters every year.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://schools.nyc.gov/Offices/mediarelations/NewsandSpeeches/2014-2015/Free+Summer+Meails.htm|title=DOE Announces Start of Annual Free Summer Meals Program for All NYC Children and Youth - 2014-2015|last=|first=|date=June 24, 2015|website=|publisher=New York City Department of Education|access-date=2017-03-21}}</ref> Over 7 million lunches were distributed in summer 2012.<ref name=":0" />
==Supermarket crisis== [[File:Super Associated East Harlem 1968 2nd Av 101 St jeh.jpg|thumb|right|upright=1.1|alt=shelves of food inside an East Harlem supermarket|Inside a supermarket in [[East Harlem]]]] New York City faces a [[supermarket shortage]] in several neighborhoods that is closely linked to health epidemics. At the request of the Mayor’s office, the Department of City Planning studied supermarket need in the city. As a result, in April 2008, the Department found a widespread shortage of supermarkets, identifying several "[[food desert]]s." It identified food deserts as a key factor in why over 700,000 people in New York City had [[Diabetes mellitus|diabetes]], over 1.1 million New Yorkers were [[Obesity|obese]], and another 2 million were [[overweight]].<ref name=going-to-market/>{{rp|1}}
Health problems are especially prevalent in minority communities. For instance, supermarkets in predominately-minority [[Harlem]] are 30 percent less common than on the predominately-white [[Upper East Side]]; while 20 percent of Upper East Side bodegas carried leafy green vegetables, only 3 percent of those in Harlem did so.<ref name=":1"/> Three million New Yorkers live in neighborhoods with high need for grocery stores and supermarkets, such as Harlem and [[Washington Heights, Manhattan|Washington Heights]] in Manhattan; [[Bushwick, Brooklyn|Bushwick]], [[East New York, Brooklyn|East New York]], and [[Sunset Park, Brooklyn|Sunset Park]] in Brooklyn; [[Corona, Queens|Corona]], [[Jamaica, Queens|Jamaica]], and [[Far Rockaway, Queens|Far Rockaway]] in Queens; the [[South Bronx]], [[Williamsbridge, Bronx|Williamsbridge]], [[Wakefield, Bronx|Wakefield]], and [[Pelham Parkway (neighborhood), Bronx|Pelham Parkway]] in the Bronx; and [[St. George, Staten Island|St. George]] and [[Stapleton, Staten Island|Stapleton]] in Staten Island show the greatest need for full-line supermarkets.<ref name=going-to-market>{{cite web|url=https://www1.nyc.gov/assets/planning/download/pdf/plans/supermarket/supermarket.pdf|title=Socioeconomic & Housing - Going to Market: New York City’s Neighborhood Grocery Store and Supermarket Shortage|website=[[Government of New York City|nyc.gov]]|publisher=[[New York City Department of City Planning]]|date=April 21, 2008|accessdate=March 20, 2017}}</ref>{{rp|2}}
In February 2008, City Council Speaker [[Christine C. Quinn|Christine Quinn]] announced the creation of a Statewide Supermarket Commission that would identify state and local policy solutions to expand supermarkets and keep them open. The Commission would be led by the Food Trust and the [[Food Bank For New York City|Food Bank for New York City]], in partnership with the City’s Food Policy Coordinator and the Food Industry Alliance.<ref name=":1">{{Cite web|url=http://fsprbuhwprtlcouncil.nyc.gov/html/pr/011_022708_prestated_greencarts.shtml|title=COUNCIL VOTES TO CREATE NEW PERMITS FOR GREEN VENDORS, BRINGING MORE FRESH PRODUCE TO UNDERSERVED COMMUNITIES|last=|first=|date=February 27, 2008|website=[[Government of New York City|nyc.gov]]|publisher=[[New York City Council|The Council of the City of New York]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080502182117/http://council.nyc.gov/html/releases/011_022708_prestated_greencarts.shtml|archive-date=2008-05-02|dead-url=no|access-date=2017-03-21}}</ref> Simultaneously, the [[United Food and Commercial Workers]] Local 1500, which represents grocery store workers, worked to create healthy food options for all New Yorkers through supermarkets, [[community-supported agriculture]], [[urban agriculture]], and farmers' markets.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://readme.readmedia.com/Union-Responds-To-New-York-City-Study-on-Lack-of-Supermarkets/124907/print|title=Union Responds To New York City Study on Lack of Supermarkets|last=|first=|date=April 22, 2008|website=readmedia.com|access-date=2017-03-21}}</ref>
===Green Cart program=== As part of an ongoing effort to increase access to healthy foods, the city created 1,000 new "Green Cart" permits in 2008. These permits were meant for street vendors who exclusively sell fresh fruits and vegetables, which must be raw and whole.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.nyc.gov/html/doh/html/cdp/cdp_pan_green_carts.shtml|title=NYC Green Carts|last=|first=|date=|website=[[Government of New York City|nyc.gov]]|publisher=[[New York City Department of Health and Mental Hygiene]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080430023505/http://www.nyc.gov/html/doh/html/cdp/cdp_pan_green_carts.shtml|archive-date=2008-04-30|dead-url=yes|access-date=2017-03-21}}</ref> These permits can be used only in neighborhoods where 15% or more of the population reported having consumed zero servings of fruits or vegetables in the previous 24 hours.<ref name=":1" /> Local businesses initially opposed the initiative, but a reduction in the number of permits allowed the program to be signed into law.<ref name=":2">{{Cite web|url=https://sipa.columbia.edu/system/files/GreenCarts_Final_June16.pdf|title=Study: NYC Green Carts Expand Access to Fresh Produce in Low-Income Neighborhoods|last=Fuchs|first=Ester R.|last2=Holloway|first2=Sarah M.|date=June 11, 2014|website=[[Columbia University|columbia.edu]]|publisher=[[Columbia University School of International and Public Affairs]]|language=en|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140725153512/https://sipa.columbia.edu/system/files/GreenCarts_Final_June16.pdf|archive-date=2014-07-25|dead-url=yes|access-date=2017-03-21|last3=Bayer|first3=Kimberly|last4=Feathers|first4=Alexandra}}</ref>{{Rp|12}} After the program was approved, the city received funding and support from several partners to help further the program.<ref name=":2" />{{Rp|13–14}}
A 2014 study by the [[School of International and Public Affairs, Columbia University|Columbia University School of International and Public Affairs]] showed that although there were only 166 Green Carts in operation, these green carts were instrumental in raising exposure to healthy foods in poorer neighborhoods in Manhattan, the Bronx, Queens, and Brooklyn.<ref name=":2" />{{Rp|27–38}} The same study found that of these Green Carts, there were none on Staten Island.<ref name=":2" />{{Rp|21–26}}<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.politico.com/states/new-york/city-hall/story/2014/07/produce-cart-program-a-modest-success-014151|title=Produce-cart program a modest success|last=Goldberg|first=Dan|date=July 7, 2014|work=Politico PRO|access-date=2017-03-21}}</ref>
== Restaurant grading system == [[File:Big Daddy's Diner (Manhattan, New York) 001.jpg|thumb|right|upright=1.1|alt=Big Daddy's Diner in Manhattan with an "A" grade displayed in the window|Big Daddy's Diner in Manhattan with an "A" grade displayed in the window]] A grading system for New York City's 24,000 restaurants was launched in July 2010.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://newyork.seriouseats.com/2010/07/a-guide-to-the-new-restaurant-grading-system.html|title=A Guide to New York's New Restaurant Grading System|last=Douglas|first=Leah|date=July 2010|website=Serious Eats|language=en|access-date=2017-05-17}}</ref><ref name=":3">{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2010/07/28/nyregion/28inspect.html|title=Letter Grading of Restaurants’ Hygiene to Begin|last=Collins|first=Glenn|date=2010-07-27|work=The New York Times|access-date=2017-05-17|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> Restaurant inspectors show up unannounced to the restaurant to inspect its hygiene, then give a ranking of A, B, or C depending on how many code violations the restaurant has. An "A" grade is considered the best grade (with 0 to 13 violations), with the highest standard for cleanliness; a "B" grade indicates 14 to 27 violations; and a "C" grade, the worst grade, indicates at least 28 violations.<ref name=":4">{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2017/05/17/nyregion/new-york-today-what-do-restaurant-grades-mean.html|title=New York Today: What Do Restaurant Grades Mean?|last=Wolfe|first=Jonathan|date=2017-05-17|work=The New York Times|access-date=2017-05-17|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> Restaurants then receive placards containing the restaurant's grades and post them in a prominent location. Each placard is embossed and tagged with a number as an anti-[[Counterfeit|counterfeiting]] measure.<ref name=":3" /> Restaurateurs who get a "B" or "C" could request a re-review of their restaurants, getting "Grade Pending" placards in the meantime.<ref name=":4" /> As part of the launch, the [[New York City Department of Health and Mental Hygiene]] hired 23 inspectors, bringing the total number of inspectors to 180. It also raised the number of annual visits from 60,000 to 85,000.<ref name=":3" />
[[Michael Bloomberg]], the then-mayor of New York City, stated that the practice was meant to reduce the number of [[Foodborne illness|foodborne illnesses]] and improve [[food safety]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB10001424052970203458604577265852174980164|title=Grading Eatery Grading|last=Saul|first=Michael Howard|date=2012-03-07|work=Wall Street Journal|access-date=2017-05-17|issn=0099-9660}}</ref> However, some restaurants avoid being regulated by registering as supermarkets or warehouses.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nydailynews.com/new-york/flimflam-menu-city-restaurants-avoid-health-dept-letter-grade-claiming-supermarkets-warehouses-article-1.1003155|title=How eateries avoid Health Dept. letter grades|last=Blau|first=Reuven|last2=Weichselbaum|first2=Simone|date=2012-01-09|website=NY Daily News|accessdate=2017-05-17}}</ref> Within 18 months of the grading system's implementation, [[Salmonellosis|salmonella]] infections dropped by 14%, but the total amount of the fines issued rose more than 145%, prompting large criticism.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://cityroom.blogs.nytimes.com/2012/03/07/restaurateurs-voice-anger-over-health-inspections/|title=Restaurateurs Voice Anger Over Health Inspections|last=Collins|first=Glenn|date=|work=City Room|access-date=2017-05-17|publisher=The New York Times Company|language=en}}</ref> In 2014, the grading system was restructured to reduce fines.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://abc7ny.com/archive/9475360/|title=NYC restaurant letter-grade system revamped by City Council|last=Lemire|first=Jonathan|date=March 21, 2014|work=ABC7 New York|access-date=2017-05-17|language=en}}</ref> In 2016, ninety-three percent of restaurants got an "A" grade, the highest percentage in the history of the grading system.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.crainsnewyork.com/article/20170512/HOSPITALITY_TOURISM/170519972/more-restaurants-than-ever-are-passing-their-health-exams|title=More restaurants are passing their health exams|last=D'Amato|first=Peter|date=2017-05-12|website=Crain's New York Business|accessdate=2017-05-17}}</ref>
== International model == Because of the way in which urban and rural New Yorkers have cooperated to create a protected ecosystem that brings healthy [[local food]] and clean water to a large urban population, New York City has become an international food systems model. The [[United Nations]] invited New York farmers, workers, retailers, and NGOs to act as representatives to the UN's [[Commission on Sustainable Development]] at [[Headquarters of the United Nations|its headquarters]] in New York City. The city hosted the UN's City and Farm Linkages Showcase in May 2008 to show New York State's urban–rural partnership to international leaders.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.un.org/esa/sustdev/csd/csd16/mg/showcase.pdf|title=City and Farm Linkages Showcase{{\}} Showcase Learning Event|publisher=[[United Nations]]|date=May 9–11, 2008|accessdate=March 20, 2017}}</ref>
